## Who Is This Review For?

This review is for the buyer who has already decided on a lab grown diamond ring and is now asking one specific question: is Blue Nile the right place to buy it?

It is also for the buyer sitting between Blue Nile, Brilliant Earth, and Ritani — wanting actual live price data to make that decision, not affiliate copy that calls every retailer equally "great" while earning a commission from all three.

I'm Farzana Hasan, a GIA Expert. I personally audited over 40 individual lab diamond listings on Blue Nile for this review, cross-referenced them against live competitor inventory, and compiled every data point a serious buyer needs before clicking "Add to Cart." My full credentials and methodology are at [Diamond Critics](https://diamondcritics.com/about-farzana/).

This article sits inside the broader [Blue Nile Review](https://diamondcritics.com/blue-nile-review/) — my full, ongoing audit of everything Blue Nile sells. If you are researching other Blue Nile categories, I have already covered [Blue Nile earrings](https://diamondcritics.com/blue-nile-earrings-review/), [Blue Nile bracelets](https://diamondcritics.com/blue-nile-bracelets-review/), [Blue Nile men's rings](https://diamondcritics.com/blue-nile-mens-rings-review/), [Blue Nile men's bracelets](https://diamondcritics.com/blue-nile-mens-bracelets-review/), and [Blue Nile men's chains](https://diamondcritics.com/blue-nile-mens-chains-review/) — all with live price data.

## What Are Blue Nile Lab Grown Diamond Rings?

Blue Nile sells lab grown diamond engagement rings as a build-your-own experience. You select a loose lab diamond separately from a setting, then combine them at checkout. This distinction matters enormously for understanding every price in this review.

When you see a dollar figure on Blue Nile's lab diamond listing pages, that number is the loose stone only. The setting — whether a solitaire, halo, pavé, or three-stone design — is priced and purchased separately. Settings at Blue Nile start around $400–$800 for 14K gold solitaires and climb to $1,500–$3,000+ for platinum or more intricate designs. Your total ring cost is always: loose lab diamond + setting. Every price table in this review reflects the loose stone cost only.

### What Makes a Blue Nile Lab Diamond?

Blue Nile sources both CVD (Chemical Vapor Deposition) and HPHT (High Pressure High Temperature) lab grown diamonds, though individual listings do not always specify the growth method. What matters for your purchase decision is the certification laboratory — and Blue Nile stocks three as of .

**[IGI (International Gemological Institute)](https://www.igi.org/)** is the dominant certifier for lab diamonds globally and fully acceptable for lab stones. **[GCAL (Gem Certification & Assurance Lab)](https://www.gcalusa.com/)** applies stricter optical performance standards and is a legitimate IGI alternative. **[GIA](https://gia.edu)** is rare for lab stones at lower carats, but Blue Nile does stock GIA-certified lab diamonds at the 4ct tier — which is genuinely unusual for any online retailer.

The rule for lab diamond certifications: both IGI and GIA are acceptable for lab-grown stones. For natural diamonds, GIA is the only certification I recommend. For lab diamonds, IGI, GIA, and GCAL are all legitimate choices. The full certification breakdown is in our [Diamond 4Cs Guide](https://diamondcritics.com/diamond-4cs/).

## Does Blue Nile Have a Good Lab Diamond Selection?

Yes — and the selection strength is concentrated exactly where it matters most for buyers who have done their research. Blue Nile's inventory is deep at the D-IF, D-FL, and E-IF tier. These are grades that would cost 5–10x more in natural diamond form, and Blue Nile stocks them in volume across 1.5ct, 2ct, 3ct, and 4ct weights.

Where Blue Nile is thinner: ultra-budget lab diamonds under $500, fancy colored lab diamonds (yellow, pink), and very small melee-equivalent lab diamonds for fully custom bespoke work. For most buyers reading this review, none of those gaps will matter.

Shape-wise, Blue Nile stocks lab grown diamonds in all major cuts — round brilliant, oval, cushion, emerald, princess, radiant, pear, marquise, and heart. This review focuses on round brilliant because it is the most purchased shape and the most forgiving for clarity evaluation. If you are considering another shape, our [Diamond Shapes Guide](https://diamondcritics.com/diamond-shapes-guide/) covers every cut in detail — including shape-specific clarity minimums that change significantly for step cuts like [emerald cut](https://diamondcritics.com/emerald-cut-diamond/) and [oval](https://diamondcritics.com/oval-cut-diamond/).

