rong></td></tr></tbody></table>

The most important data point here is the gap between D-IF and D-FL. At 1.50ct, two D-IF IGI Ideal stones start at **[$2,930](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29116725?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blue_nile_reviews)**. The exact same carat, color, and cut in D-FL jumps to **[$3,780](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28614776?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blue_nile_reviews)**. That is an $850 premium for a clarity distinction that disappears the moment the stone is set in a ring. I call this **The Lab FL Tax** — and at 1.50ct, it is never worth paying.

A round brilliant's 57 facets create enough light dispersion that any theoretical residual graining in an IF-graded lab stone is optically undetectable in a setting. FL adds zero visible benefit over IF here. Buy the D-IF. Add the $850 to your setting budget or keep it.

One more thing worth flagging: the GCAL D-IF at **[$3,330](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28785520?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blue_nile_reviews)** costs $400 more than the IGI D-IF despite identical graded specs. And the **[$5,090](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29104397?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blue_nile_reviews)** D-FL outlier at the bottom is $1,310 more than identical-grade stones sitting above it — always check the individual certificate for table %, depth %, and fluorescence before paying any within-grade premium.

