"https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28794458?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&amp;a_cid=55e51e63&amp;chan=blue_nile_reviews">$20,250</a></strong></td></tr><tr><td>IGI</td><td>4.00ct</td><td>D</td><td>FL</td><td>Ideal</td><td><strong><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28595075?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&amp;a_cid=55e51e63&amp;chan=blue_nile_reviews">$20,250</a></strong></td></tr><tr><td>IGI</td><td>4.00ct</td><td>D</td><td>FL</td><td>Ideal</td><td><strong><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28378373?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&amp;a_cid=55e51e63&amp;chan=blue_nile_reviews">$20,250</a></strong></td></tr><tr><td>IGI</td><td>4.00ct</td><td>D</td><td>IF</td><td>Ideal</td><td><strong><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/27512216?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&amp;a_cid=55e51e63&amp;chan=blue_nile_reviews">$21,110</a></strong></td></tr><tr><td>IGI</td><td>4.00ct</td><td>D</td><td>IF</td><td>Ideal</td><td><strong><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/27512217?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&amp;a_cid=55e51e63&amp;chan=blue_nile_reviews">$21,110</a></strong></td></tr><tr><td>IGI</td><td>4.00ct</td><td>D</td><td>IF</td><td>Ideal</td><td><strong><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/27482246?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&amp;a_cid=55e51e63&amp;chan=blue_nile_reviews">$21,110</a></strong></td></tr><tr><td>IGI</td><td>4.00ct</td><td>D</td><td>FL</td><td>Ideal</td><td><strong><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28953635?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&amp;a_cid=55e51e63&amp;chan=blue_nile_reviews">$21,540</a></strong></td></tr></tbody></table>

Three things stand out at 4ct. First, the **4ct Price Cluster Phenomenon**: D-IF and D-FL IGI stones are priced identically at **$20,250** across the board, regardless of clarity grade. The market has already corrected for the IF vs FL distinction at 4ct because it recognizes — correctly — that it is commercially meaningless.

Second, the **E-IF exception is the smartest buy in this entire audit**. The 4ct E-IF IGI at **[$12,320](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/27420794?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blue_nile_reviews)** is nearly $8,000 less than its D-IF equivalents.

At 4ct in a prong or bezel setting, the one color grade difference between D and E is invisible to the naked eye in any lighting condition. If budget matters at this weight, E-IF is where you go.

Third, Blue Nile stocks GIA-certified 4ct D-IF lab diamonds — starting at **[$16,120](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/27425634?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blue_nile_reviews)**. You are not getting a better diamond by choosing GIA over IGI at 4ct lab — but if the GIA name on the certificate matters to you personally, these stones exist here and essentially nowhere else online at this volume.

## How Does Blue Nile Compare to Brilliant Earth and Ritani?

Blue Nile is cheaper than Brilliant Earth by 10–20% on equivalent lab diamond grades, and cheaper than Ritani by approximately 15–25% when total ring costs are compared at the same quality level. But cheaper is not always better — so here is the honest comparison.

### Complete Ring Comparison — Approx. 1.50ct D-VS1 Round Ideal, 14K White Gold Solitaire

<table class="dc-custom-table"><thead><tr><th>Retailer</th><th>Approx. Total Ring Price</th><th>What You're Paying For</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Blue Nile</strong></td><td>$2,200–$2,800</td><td>The diamond itself. Full grade transparency, build-your-own, no showrooms.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Brilliant Earth</strong></td><td>$2,990–$3,590</td><td>The diamond + ethical sourcing story + access to 42 in-person showrooms.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Ritani</strong></td><td>$3,200–$4,500</td><td>The diamond + NYC handcrafted settings + in-person preview program.</td></tr></tbody></table>

### Loose Stone Comparison — 2.00ct D-IF Round Ideal Lab Diamond

<table class="dc-custom-table"><thead><tr><th>Retailer</th><th>Approx. Price</th><th>Certification</th><th>Notes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Blue Nile</strong></td><td><strong><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28638054?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&amp;a_cid=55e51e63&amp;chan=blue_nile_reviews">$5,780</a></strong></td><td>GCAL</td><td>Live audited price. Best value at this grade.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Brilliant Earth</strong></td><td>~$6,200–$7,500</td><td>IGI</td><td>10–20% premium; includes brand story and showroom access.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Ritani</strong></td><td>~$7,000+ with setting</td><td>IGI</td><td>Most quotes include setting; higher base due to handcraft premium.</td></tr></tbody></table>

**Where Brilliant Earth beats Blue Nile:** Brilliant Earth operates 42 physical showrooms across the US — including Beverly Hills — where you can preview rings in person before committing.

For buyers who need to hold a ring before buying, that is a real advantage Blue Nile simply cannot replicate. Their ethical sourcing credentials — carbon-neutral shipping, 100% recycled metals, blockchain diamond traceability — are also real and documented, not marketing spin. If sustainability matters to your purchase, Brilliant Earth earns its premium.

**Where Ritani beats Blue Nile:** Ritani hand-fabricates their settings in New York — not cast commercially, but actually made by hand. This is a meaningful differentiator for complex pavé and halo designs.

They also offer a "Diamond Pro" preview program on orders over $1,500, where a jewelry professional meets you locally with the actual stone before you commit — no charge, no obligation. For a 3ct or 4ct purchase, that kind of in-person preview has real value.

**Where Blue Nile wins:** On price transparency and stone value per dollar, Blue Nile is better than both. The inventory depth at D-IF and D-FL across 3ct and 4ct is unmatched online. For a buyer who has done the research — or is using this review as their research — Blue Nile delivers more diamond for the money than any competitor tested.

